'''Pape Bouna Thiaw''' (born 5 February 1981) is a Senegalese [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and a former player who played as a [[forward (association football)|forward]]. He is the currently head coach of the [[Senegal national football team]].

==Playing career==
He played for several clubs in France, Switzerland and Spain, as well as [[FC Dynamo Moscow|Dynamo Moscow]] in Russia on a six-month loan from [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]].

He played for [[Senegal national football team]] and was a participant at the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]]. He scored 5 goals for his country.

==Coaching career==
Thiaw was the manager of the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal A' national team]] that won the [[2022 African Nations Championship]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=18 December 2022|title=Senegal gear up for a promising CHAN return |url=https://www.cafonline.com/total-african-nations-championship/2022/news/senegal-gear-up-for-a-promising-chan-return|website=[[Confedération Africaine du Football|CAFOnline.com]]|access-date=8 January 2023}}</ref> African Nations Championship limits the squads to players from the domestic league. The main Senegal squad that participates in the [[FIFA World Cup]] and [[Africa Cup of Nations]] and includes players from the foreign clubs was managed by [[Aliou Cissé]]. Thiaw was appointed coach of the Senegal national football team on 13 December 2024, following the latter dismissal two month before.<ref>{{Cite web|date=13 December 2024|title=Afrique foot Football: Pape Thiaw choisi pour succèder à Aliou Cissé comme sélectionneur du Sénégal |url=https://www.rfi.fr/fr/afrique-foot/20241213-football-pape-thiaw-choisi-pour-succ%C3%A8der-%C3%A0-aliou-ciss%C3%A9-comme-s%C3%A9lectionneur-du-s%C3%A9n%C3%A9gal|website=www.rfi.fr|access-date=13 December 2024}}</ref>

In October 2025, he led Senegal to qualify to the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Senegal Defeats Mauritania and Qualifies for the 2026 World Cup with a Sadio Mané Double | url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/articles/senegal-defeats-mauritania-and-qualifies-for-the-2026-world-cup-with-a-sadio-man%C3%A9-double-2025-10-14 |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=14 October 2025 }}</ref> In January 2026, Thiaw coached Senegal to at the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/live-blogs/senegal-vs-morocco-afcon-2025-final-score-result/DQtU75DqxAoW/ |title=Senegal beat Morocco thanks to Gueye strike in extraordinary AFCON 2025 final: Live updates and reaction |publisher=The New York Times |date=19 January 2026 }}</ref>  During the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations final|AFCON final]], he urged his players to leave the field in protest after the referee awarded Morocco a penalty in stoppage time, which prompted disciplinary proceedings against him after the match.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-us/soccer/africa-cup-of-nations/articles/senegal-coach-apologizes-after-afcon-final-scandal-2026-01-19 |title=Senegal Coach Apologizes After AFCON Final Scandal |publisher=beIN SPORTS |date=19 January 2026 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://en.africatopsports.com/2026/01/19/afcon-2025-caf-could-heavily-sanction-pape-thiaw/ |title=AFCON 2025: CAF could heavily sanction Pape Thiaw |publisher=Africa Top Sports |date=19 January 2026 }}</ref> This led to him being banned for five games and fined $100,000 for "unsporting conduct" and "bringing the game into disrepute" by the [[Confederation of African Football]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c24gy9d52vno |title=Senegal boss Thiaw banned after Afcon final chaos |publisher=BBC |date=29 January 2026 }}</ref>

